#: cambalache/app/cmb_help_window.ui:46
msgid ""
"Cambalache is a WYSIWYG (What You See Is What You Get) tool that allows you "
"to create and edit user interfaces for Gtk 4 and 3 applications.\n"
"\n"
"Gtk provides all the necessary building blocks to create desktop and mobile "
"application such as windows, labels, buttons, text boxes, dialogs.\n"
"\n"
"These blocks are called widgets and you can use this application to arrange "
"them, modify their properties and define event connections to your "
"application source code."
msgstr ""

#: cambalache/app/cmb_help_window.ui:60
msgid "Etymology"
msgstr ""

#: cambalache/app/cmb_help_window.ui:70
msgid ""
"Cambalache (pronounced /kamba'latʃe/) means second-hand shop, junk shop, the "
"windows of such places or something messy.\n"
"\n"
"It is also a very famous Tango from the 30's by Enrique Discépolo, you can "
"find my favorite interpretation by Julio Sosa <a href=\"https://"
"www.youtube.com/watch?v=T0kTiKCC3UI\" title=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?"
"v=T0kTiKCC3UI\">here</a>.\n"
"\n"
"Why this name?\n"
"\n"
"While I know it is a weird and hard to pronounce name specially for English "
"native speaker I wanted to make it clear just by reading the name that it is "
"an application made in South America and hopefully encourage more people "
"from the area to contribute and be part of the open source community."
msgstr ""

#: cambalache/app/cmb_help_window.ui:87
msgid "Target audience"
msgstr ""

#: cambalache/app/cmb_help_window.ui:97
msgid ""
"Cambalache has one simple goal, spare you from writing XML UI files by "
"hand.\n"
"\n"
"Which means the intended audience are developers familiar with Gtk and the "
"GtkBuilder format.\n"
"\n"
"If you are not, I recommend following the excellent  <a href=\"https://"
"www.gtk.org/docs/getting-started/\" title=\"https://www.gtk.org/docs/getting-"
"started/\">Gtk documentation</a> and get familiar with the concepts of "
"widgets, properties, signals and layout/container widgets like GtkBox and "
"GtkGrid.\n"
"\n"
"It is also a good idea to write some simple GtkBuilder files by hand to "
"learn the fundamentals of GtkBuilder before starting to use this application "
"for your day to day work."
msgstr ""

#: cambalache/app/cmb_help_window.ui:120
#, fuzzy
msgid "Introduction"
msgstr "Internationaal"

#: cambalache/app/cmb_help_window.ui:137 cambalache/app/cmb_help_window.ui:278
msgid "Architecture"
msgstr ""

#: cambalache/app/cmb_help_window.ui:147
msgid "Cambalache relies heavily on the model view controller design pattern."
msgstr ""

#: cambalache/app/cmb_help_window.ui:158 cambalache/cmb_view.ui:126
#, fuzzy
msgid "Data Model"
msgstr "Model"

#: cambalache/app/cmb_help_window.ui:168
msgid ""
"The data model is a SQLite relational DB which models the GObject type "
"system and uses triggers to keep the undo/redo history stack."
msgstr ""

#: cambalache/app/cmb_help_window.ui:184
msgid ""
"All the type data is populated from GObject introspection files (Gir files) "
"by a script called <b>cmb-catalog-gen</b> and stored in one catalog file per "
"widget library and loaded at initialization time."
msgstr ""

#: cambalache/app/cmb_help_window.ui:196 cambalache/app/cmb_shortcuts.ui:74
#: cambalache/app/cmb_window.ui:489
msgid "Workspace"
msgstr "Werkruimte"

#: cambalache/app/cmb_help_window.ui:206
msgid ""
"The workspace view runs in a separate process called <b>Merengue</b> and is "
"responsible to create and update the widgets you are editing according to "
"your actions.\n"
"\n"
"These widgets are embedded in the main UI using a Wayland compositor widget "
"for seamless integration. This allows  support not only for Gtk 4 but also "
"version 3.\n"
"\n"
"This split is critical for stability as it prevents the widgets you are "
"creating from taking down the whole application. \n"
"\n"
"Think of widgets that call abort() if a property is not set, which is "
"correct from the type point of view but requires custom code to make sure "
"these conditions are not reached while previewing."
msgstr ""

#: cambalache/app/cmb_help_window.ui:230
#, fuzzy
msgid "Editor UI"
msgstr "UI-bewerker"

#: cambalache/app/cmb_help_window.ui:240
msgid ""
"The controller is a regular Gtk 4 application that allows the user to create "
"multiple UI files and edit object properties and signals. It's design is "
"heavily influenced by Glade's UI because well... I made it and also did not "
"wanted to spend the little cycles I had in a new UI."
msgstr ""

#: cambalache/app/cmb_help_window.ui:256
msgid "The interface is ofcourse made with Cambalache."
msgstr ""

#: cambalache/app/cmb_help_window.ui:294 cambalache/app/cmb_help_window.ui:477
#: cambalache/cmb_project_settings.ui:17
msgid "Catalogs"
msgstr ""

#: cambalache/app/cmb_help_window.ui:304
msgid ""
"Widget catalogs are XML files containing all the metadata needed to use "
"widgets from different libraries in Cambalache.\n"
"\n"
"This includes object types, interfaces, enumerations, flags, properties and "
"signals.\n"
"\n"
"These are created using GObject introspection data, the actual runtime "
"objects and extra metadata with a tool called <b>cmb-catalog-gen</b>"
msgstr ""

#: cambalache/app/cmb_help_window.ui:319
msgid ""
"<b>NOTE:</b> Keep in mind this tool and the file format is not stable and "
"will change in the near future."
msgstr ""

#: cambalache/app/cmb_help_window.ui:332
#, fuzzy
msgid "Creating a new catalog"
msgstr "Nieuw project aanmaken"

#: cambalache/app/cmb_help_window.ui:343
msgid ""
"To create a simple catalog for a library like Casilda all you need is "
"specify with Gtk version the library targets, the catalog dependencies and "
"the gir file.\n"
"The tool will read all the required metadata from the gir file and "
"instantiate each object type to get things like properties defaults and such."
msgstr ""

#: cambalache/app/cmb_help_window.ui:367
msgid "In this case there is only one type with one property."
msgstr ""

#: cambalache/app/cmb_help_window.ui:400
msgid "Built in catalogs"
msgstr ""

#: cambalache/app/cmb_help_window.ui:411
msgid ""
"Internally Cambalache use the same workflow to create all the catalogs "
"needed for Gtk.\n"
"\n"
"If you are interested you can take a look at the <a href=\"https://"
"gitlab.gnome.org/jpu/cambalache/-/blob/main/catalogs/Makefile\" "
"title=\"https://gitlab.gnome.org/jpu/\">Makefile</a> used to generate all "
"the built in catalogs."
msgstr ""

#: cambalache/app/cmb_help_window.ui:423
msgid "3rd party catalogs"
msgstr ""

#: cambalache/app/cmb_help_window.ui:434
msgid ""
"By default Cambalache also includes 3rd party catalogs for libraries like "
"Adwaita and WebkitGtk but other 3rd party libraries could ship their own "
"catalogs and install them in any of the system data dirs as returned by "
"<span font-family=\"monospace\">GLib.get_system_data_dirs()</span>\n"
"\n"
"User catalogs can be installed in <span font-"
"family=\"monospace\">~/.cambalache/catalogs</span>"
msgstr ""

#: cambalache/app/cmb_help_window.ui:446
#, fuzzy
msgid "Workspace plugins"
msgstr "Werkruimte"

#: cambalache/app/cmb_help_window.ui:457
msgid ""
"Workspace integration requires extra code to do things like add placeholders "
"to containers, make sure objects can be shown, selected, etc.\n"
"\n"
"Currently this is not documented or exposed for 3rd party libraries but "
"there are plans to add support for it once the catalog format is more "
"stable.\n"
"\n"
"If you are interested in adding support for your library please contact us "
"at the matrix channel."
msgstr ""

#: cambalache/app/cmb_help_window.ui:496 cambalache/app/cmb_help_window.ui:637
#, fuzzy
msgid "Projects"
msgstr "Project"

#: cambalache/app/cmb_help_window.ui:506
msgid ""
"Back in the day it was common practice to have one big XML file describing "
"all windows and dialogs of an application.\n"
"\n"
"This started to change with the introduction of composite widgets using <a "
"href=\"https://docs.gtk.org/gtk4/class.Widget.html#building-composite-"
"widgets-from-template-xml\">XML templates</a> which makes creating custom "
"widgets really easy. This allows you to split UI and logic in smaller and "
"simpler components that can be reused just like any other Gtk widget making "
"things easier to maintain.\n"
"\n"
"For this reason Cambalache workflow is built around projects where you can "
"create or import all files needed to define your application GUI."
msgstr ""

#: cambalache/app/cmb_help_window.ui:520
#, fuzzy
msgid "Supported types"
msgstr "Sponsors"

#: cambalache/app/cmb_help_window.ui:531
msgid ""
"    • <a href=\"https://docs.gtk.org/gtk4/class.Builder.html#gtkbuilder-ui-"
"definitions\" title=\"https://docs.gtk.org/gtk4/"
"class.Builder.html#gtkbuilder-ui-definitions\">GtkBuilder</a> - XML UI files "
"and templates\n"
"    • <a href=\"https://gnome.pages.gitlab.gnome.org/blueprint-compiler/\" "
"title=\"https://gnome.pages.gitlab.gnome.org/blueprint-compiler/"
"\">Blueprint</a> - markup language\n"
"    • <a href=\"https://docs.gtk.org/gio/struct.Resource.html\" "
"title=\"https://docs.gtk.org/gio/struct.Resource.html\">GResources</a> - XML "
"bundle definitions\n"
"    • <a href=\"https://docs.gtk.org/gtk4/css-overview.html\" "
"title=\"https://docs.gtk.org/gtk4/css-overview.html\">CSS</a> - Gtk "
"stylesheets"
msgstr ""

#: cambalache/app/cmb_help_window.ui:545
msgid ""
"<b>NOTE:</b> Please keep in mind that when importing a UI file there will be "
"differences on the output the first time its saved because Cambalache "
"outputs properties, signals and other elements in a particular order.\n"
"Once saved the output should be stable, if not, please file an issue."
msgstr ""

#: cambalache/app/cmb_help_window.ui:559
#, fuzzy
msgid "Creating a new project"
msgstr "Nieuw project aanmaken"

#: cambalache/app/cmb_help_window.ui:572
msgid ""
"To create a new project you can use Ctrl+N shortcut or activate Menu -> New "
"Project menu button to open the \"New Project\" screen where you can select "
"a filename, location and an initial UI for your project."
msgstr ""

#: cambalache/app/cmb_help_window.ui:587
msgid ""
"All files will be relative to the project file so its better to choose a "
"toplevel directory in your project.\n"
"\n"
"Once created you can start adding UI files to your project or if you already "
"have UI files you can manually import individual files or import everything "
"suported using Menu -> Import directory.\n"
"\n"
"This will scan the selected directory for all supported files and load them "
"in the right order."
msgstr ""

#: cambalache/app/cmb_help_window.ui:600
#, fuzzy
msgid "Project Settings"
msgstr "Projectweergave"

#: cambalache/app/cmb_help_window.ui:613
msgid ""
"The project settings dialog allows you to select which extra widget "
"libraries (Catalogs) will be available to use in the project. So if you are "
"makeing a GNOME application you will need Adwaita widgets. \n"
"\n"
"It also lets you specify a list of directories with icons for named icons to "
"work in the preview."
msgstr ""

#: cambalache/app/cmb_help_window.ui:653 cambalache/app/cmb_help_window.ui:801
msgid "Creating Widgets"
msgstr ""

#: cambalache/app/cmb_help_window.ui:663
msgid ""
"Once the project is setup you can start creating widgets in any UI file.\n"
"For convenience a UI file named as the project is created by default but you "
"can add more UI files using the Add button in the header bar or the Add file "
"submenu in the main menu."
msgstr ""

#: cambalache/app/cmb_help_window.ui:673
#, fuzzy
msgid "Type Chooser"
msgstr "Nieuw typeselectiebalk"

#: cambalache/app/cmb_help_window.ui:684
msgid ""
"Object types are accessible in the chooser bar by category.\n"
"\n"
"    • <b>Toplevel</b>: Windows, dialogs, popovers, things that do not have a "
"parent\n"
"    • <b>Layout</b>: Box, Grid things used to arrage widgets in different "
"layouts\n"
"    • <b>Control</b>: Button, entry, spin things used to control thing in "
"your application\n"
"    • <b>Display</b>: label, view, things to display information\n"
"    • <b>Model</b>: Store, buffers, list models things that store data\n"
"\n"
"Objects in the toplevel category are created immediately after selecting one "
"in the dropdown menu."
msgstr ""

#: cambalache/app/cmb_help_window.ui:708
msgid ""
"Objects in other categories are created by first selecting a type and then "
"clicking on a placeholder or using the context menu in the object "
"hierarchy.\n"
"\n"
"Holding Alt while selecting a type will force the creation of a new object "
"in the currently selected object. This is particularly useful for adding "
"children to types that do not have placeholder support yet."
msgstr ""

#: cambalache/app/cmb_help_window.ui:719
#, fuzzy
msgid "Placeholders"
msgstr "Ondersteuning voor plaatshouders in werkruimte"

#: cambalache/app/cmb_help_window.ui:730
msgid ""
"A placeholder is a workspace widget that looks like a grid added to "
"container objects to hold a place for future widgets.\n"
"\n"
"After selecting a type you can create a new object where the placeholder is "
"by clicking on it.\n"
"\n"
"Another convenient way to add a child is to double click on a placeholder "
"when no type is selected which will open a dropdown menu with a list of "
"possible types to create."
msgstr ""

#: cambalache/app/cmb_help_window.ui:749 cambalache/app/cmb_window.ui:354
msgid "Object Editor"
msgstr "Objectbewerker"

#: cambalache/app/cmb_help_window.ui:760
msgid ""
"Once you created an object you can set its properties, signals and "
"Accessibility properties in the object editor panel on the right."
msgstr ""

#: cambalache/app/cmb_help_window.ui:775
#, fuzzy
msgid "Undo / Redo"
msgstr "Stapel om acties ongedaan te maken of opnieuw te doen"

#: cambalache/app/cmb_help_window.ui:786
msgid ""
"Every action can be undone by using the undo/redo button in the header bar."
msgstr ""

#: cambalache/app/cmb_help_window.ui:817 cambalache/app/cmb_help_window.ui:943
#, fuzzy
msgid "Gtk Templates"
msgstr "Sjabloon"

#: cambalache/app/cmb_help_window.ui:827
msgid ""
"Templates are a convenient way of creating new UI components made out of "
"other components from a UI XML definition.\n"
"\n"
"A template is bound to a type and will create all the widgets defined in the "
"XML file automatically every time you instantiate an object. It also provide "
"a way to bind objects to instance fields and signals to callbacks.\n"
"\n"
"For more information please refer to <a href=\"https://developer.gnome.org/"
"documentation/tutorials/widget-templates.html\" title=\"https://"
"developer.gnome.org/documentation/tutorials/widget-templates.html\">Gtk "
"documentation</a>"
msgstr ""

#: cambalache/app/cmb_help_window.ui:842
#, fuzzy
msgid "Creating a new template"
msgstr "(sjabloon)"

#: cambalache/app/cmb_help_window.ui:853
msgid ""
"To create a new template all you need to do is create a new UI file, add a "
"toplevel widget which will be the parent class of the template type and "
"select the template flag in the property editor."
msgstr ""

#: cambalache/app/cmb_help_window.ui:871
msgid "Object id will be used as the new type name"
msgstr ""

#: cambalache/app/cmb_help_window.ui:885
#, fuzzy
msgid "Using templates"
msgstr "(sjabloon)"

#: cambalache/app/cmb_help_window.ui:897
msgid ""
"Once a template is defined it will be available immediately to use as a new "
"type in the project. \n"
"\n"
"The type is not associated to any specific category so it will only be "
"available in the global type search, the uncategorized drowdown or on "
"placeholder double click."
msgstr ""

#: cambalache/app/cmb_help_window.ui:919
msgid ""
"Keep in mind that Cambalache only knows the name and parent type, so new "
"properties and signals wont be available. But do not worry I plan to add "
"support for defining properties and signals in Cambalache soon, in the mean "
"time it is possible to define them using XML fragments.\n"
msgstr ""

#: cambalache/app/cmb_help_window.ui:959 cambalache/app/cmb_help_window.ui:1064
